To find the inverse function for f(x), we write ~y = 2x-3~ and solve for x.
        y \amp = 2x-3 \amp \amp \blert{\text{Add 3 to both sides.}}
            y+3 \amp = 2x \amp \amp \blert{\text{Divide both sides by 2.}}
            \dfrac{y+3}{2} \amp = x
        We can use any variables for a function, so we switch back to x for the input and y for the output:  ~y = \dfrac{x+3}{2}~. Thus, the inverse function is
            j(x)=\dfrac{x+3}{2}

To find the inverse function for f(x), we write ~y = \sqrt[3]{x-4}~ and solve for x.
        y \amp = \sqrt[3]{x-4} \amp \amp \blert{\text{Cube both sides.}}
            y^3 \amp = x-4 \amp \amp \blert{\text{Add 4 to both sides.}}
            y^3+4 \amp = x
        We can use any variables for a function, so we switch back to x for the input and y for the output:  
        j(x)=x^3+4
